<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1864-12-26T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1864-12-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="34" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d34">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Adams</persName></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 1201]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1864-12-26"><hi rend="italic">December</hi> 26<hi rend="italic">,</hi>
                                1864</date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> Your despatch of December 1, No. 823, has
                            been received, together with a copy of a note which Earl Russell has
                            written to James M. Mason, John Slidell and Dudley Mann. If the present
                            government of her Majesty were less just or generous towards the United
                            States than they are, I might think it wise to raise a question upon
                            that extraordinary communication.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD,</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Charles Francis Adams,</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>